description: Another survivor from the Hot Springs Club days.
Undoubtedly, some were planted by the Montecito Hot Springs Club, but that was decades ago and they have continued to reproduce and grow on their own.

This perhaps former sagebrush steppe (Artemisia tridentata wyomingensis is sporadic throughout this area) is dominated by Atriplex confertifolia (maybe reseeded?) and an abundance of annual exotics, one of which is Bromus tectorum (the others including Kochia, Salsola, and Sisymbrium). This site lies along the Unionville Road along the east side of the West Humboldt Range, north of Unionville, Nevada.

description:
Post-fire sagebrush steppe vegetation in the region of northeastern Nevada includes much more than Bromus tectorum. Erodium cicutarium and Sisymbrium altissimum are often more abundant, and native species of Argemone, Asclepias, Elymus, Lygodesmia, Poa, and Tetradymia, for example, are common. Such sites are perhaps degraded such that cheatgrass can't compete but then this argues against a cheatgrass-fire cycle. This site wasn't all that degraded because it was covered with sagebrush steppe until this fire that occurred a few years before this photo was taken.

Photo documentation and species delimitation at https://www.flickr.com/photos/plant_diversity/albums/72157685462359140

description: Please forgive the quality of the specimen. I was twelve when I collected it.

In contrast to the sagebrush steppe in eastern Nevada, the sagebrush steppe in the region around Winnemucca coexists with an abundance of cheatgrass. Notably, cheatgrass cover may be as dense or more so in pre-fire than post-fire sagebrush steppe. Such cheatgrass abundance is regional in the low elevations of the Lahontan Lake bed and occurs in abundance regardless of fire, elevation, and substrate.

During the early 1900's, Winnemucca Mountain was set afire as part of 4th of July displays while cheatgrass was promoted on the range as early season livestock forage (Young & Clements, Cheatgrass: Fire and Forage on the Range)

description: This species of Artemisia can be very compact and appear similar to Artemisia arbuscula (little sagebrush). A shrub with many thin stems, where the trunks are not much over 1 cm broad, are most distinctive of snowfield sagebrush. The similar Artemisia tridentata ssp. vaseyana (mountain big sagebrush) also has a flat-topped canopy but is a few-stemmed thick-trunked shrub. The tridentate terminal lobes of each leaf of snowfield sagebrush have somewhat overlapping margins, which also distinguishes this species from the similar Artemisia arbuscula (little sagebrush).

description: I don't know what kind of Dragonfly this is.

Three of these blue-black wasps were on a single California Buckwheat (Eriogonum fasciculatum var. foliolosum) shrub in sage scrub at the Claremont Colleges' Bernard Field Station. The wasps were moving about quickly and were quite twitchy, so they were rather hard to photograph. Also, because they moved about so much, I couldn't keep straight which individual was which, so these photos may be of the same or different individuals. These photos were originally posted to BugGuide (https://bugguide.net/node/view/834084), where Nick Fensler identified the wasp as Aporus sp., and iNat's computer vision agrees. The size of the images was reduced for posting on BugGuide. If larger images are required for identification or other purposes, please let me know. I also have some additional photos, so please let me know if specific features not shown here are required for identification, and I'll see if they show in any other photos.

I observed this lizard, photos attached, in my very small backyard in Irvine, a 2005 development. It was a nice warm day in August 2013. I have only succulent plants in my small yard with most in pots, that have been growing over 5 years. Other side of my block wall is community landscaping. There has been a lot of dirt moving, for housing developments across the Jeffery street. They are also building an extension of nature trail along the drainage from the hills. description: Popped up overnight in my back yard.

The Myotis was detected with a Binary Acoustic Technology (BAT) IFR-IV bioacoustic detector.  The call was identified as a bat by myself and Jim Dines of the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County.  The species was identified as a 40 KHz Myotis with Sonobat software.  We want to process more calls before we identify it as a small-footed myotis or other myotis species within the same range.  The Free-tailed Bat and the Myotis Bat we just documented are new records for Exposition Park. They join just one other bat species previously documented here based upon prepared specimens in the Museum’s mammal collection: the Hoary Bat.

One of the California Ground Squirrel dens I had observed in the park.  This one had been established under the stump of a large tree.
A small flock of Bushtits that I had encountered around noon in the campground.  They were gleaning around the branches of several trees, making their way deeper into the park.

A pair of adult Western Fence Lizards that I encountered in and around the creek bed.  The first one I stumbled upon while it was sunning itself on a boulder at the edge of the creek bed.  The second one I found clinging to the side of a small tree near the picnic tables.

Two of the hatchling Western Fence Lizards that I encountered in and around the creek bed.  One had been sunning itself on top of a tree stump, and right above a ground squirrel den.  The other was in the creek bed, and I nearly stepped on, just before realizing it was there.
A pair of adult Side-blotched Lizards that I found sunning themselves on the larger boulders within the creek bed, who then retreated to the nearest cover when I accidentally startled them.
Throughout the creek bed, I saw many hatchling Side-blotched.  I didn't notice most of them until they started to dart over the gravel and boulders when they felt I got too close to them.
I encountered this Lepidopteran while I was hiking in the drier sections of the creek bed around noon.
I encountered a small group of Dark-eyed Juncos around the park's picnic tables.  They proved very difficult to photograph, as they kept darting around every time I raised my camera.

Around the larger pools of water, I noticed the fresh carcasses of several Crayfish laying on top of the mats of algae.  I did spot a live individual in the pool itself, but it vanished under the algae mats before I could photograph it too.

I encountered this very vocal Red-shouldered Hawk over the larger pools of the creek bed around noon.  I first sighted it when the hawk flew past me before landing on the branch of a tree on the opposite bank of the creek.  Unfortunately, my camera kept focusing on the leaves in the mid-ground, rather than the hawk, and I could not find a better angle to take any photos from either.  Thus a positive identification came from its calls and the black and light grayish banding across the wings and tail feathers.

I had been hiking through the creek bed round noon and found my way to one of the shallow pools that remained a little further up river.  When I reached the edge of the pool, I accidentally started a pair of what I believe were Least Bitterns on the opposite side of the pool.  One of them retreated into the vegetation, while the other flew further upstream.  I only managed to take this one photo of the latter in flight, before losing sight of both.
